6.Summary:
Apache Tomcat is prone to a remote code execution vulnerability
  (dubbed 'Ghostcat') in the AJP connector.
6.Specific Result:
It was possible to read the file "/WEB-INF/web.xml" through the AJP connector.
Result:
AB u\x0004 Ã\x0088 \x0002OK  \x0003Â \x0007 =JSESSIONID=331555809B51B328278026CAE5D4AD67; Path=/; HttpOnly Â \x0001 \x001Ctext/html;charset=ISO-8859-1 Â \x0003 \x0003589 AB\x0002Q\x0003\x0002M<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<web-app xmlns="http://java.sun.com/xml/ns/javaee"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://java.sun.com/xml/ns/javaee http://java.sun.com/xml/ns/javaee/web-app_3_0.xsd"
         version="3.0">
    <context-param>
        <param-name>
            org.jboss.jbossfaces.WAR_BUNDLES_JSF_IMPL
        </param-name>
        <param-value>true</param-value>
    </context-param>
    <welcome-file-list>
        <welcome-file>index.jsp</welcome-file>
    </welcome-file-list>
</web-app> AB \x0002\x0005\x0001
6.Solution:
Update Apache Tomcat to version 7.0.100, 8.5.51, 9.0.31 or later. For other products
  using Tomcat please contact the vendor for more information on fixed versions.
6.Affected Software/OS:
Apache Tomcat versions prior 7.0.100, 8.5.51 or 9.0.31 when the AJP connector
  is enabled.
  Other products like JBoss or Wildfly which are using Tomcat might be affected as well.
6.Vulnerability Insight:
Apache Tomcat server has a file containing vulnerability, which can be used by
  an attacker to read or include any files in all webapp directories on Tomcat, such as webapp configuration files
  or source code.
6.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Sends a crafted AJP request and checks the response.

Apache Tomcat AJP RCE Vulnerability (Ghostcat)
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.143545)
Version used: 2021-07-22T02:00:50Z

7.NVT Name: Apache Tomcat SecurityManager Information Disclosure Vulnerability (Windows)
7.Summary: Apache Tomcat is prone to an information disclosure vulnerability.
7.Specific Result:
Installed version: 7.0.
Fixed version:     7.0.76
Installation
path / port:       443/tcp
7.Impact:
Successful exploitation will allow remote
  attackers to obtain sensitive information from requests other then their own.
7.Affected Software/OS:
Apache Tomcat versions 9.0.0.M1 to 9.0.0.M17,
  Apache Tomcat versions 8.5.0 to 8.5.11,
  Apache Tomcat versions 8.0.0.RC1 to 8.0.41 and
  Apache Tomcat versions 7.0.0 to 7.0.75 on Windows
7.Vulnerability Insight:
A some calls to application listeners
  did not use the appropriate facade object. When running an untrusted
  application under a SecurityManager, it was therefore possible for
  that untrusted application to retain a reference to the request or
  response object and thereby access and/or modify information associated
   with another web application.
7.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.

(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.810764)

10.NVT Name: Apache Tomcat Security Manager Bypass Vulnerability - 01 - Feb16 (Windows)
10.Summary: Apache Tomcat is prone to a security manager bypass vulnerability.
10.Specific Result:
Installed version: 7.0.
Fixed version:     7.0.68
Installation
path / port:       8443/tcp
10.Impact:
Successful exploitation will allow remote
  authenticated users to bypass intended SecurityManager restrictions and execute
  arbitrary code in a privileged context and read arbitrary HTTP requests, and
  consequently discover session ID values.
10.Solution:
Upgrade to version 6.0.45 or 7.0.68 or
  8.0.32 or 9.0.0.M3 or later.
10.Affected Software/OS:
Apache Tomcat 6.0.0 before 6.0.45, and
  7.0.0 before 7.0.68, 8.0.0.RC1 before 8.0.31, and 9.0.0.M1 on Windows.
10.Vulnerability Insight:
The flaw exists due to an improper validation
  of several session persistence mechanisms and the StatusManagerServlet loaded
  by a web application when a security manager was configured.
10.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.
Details:
Apache Tomcat Security Manager Bypass Vulnerability - 01 - Feb16 (Windows)
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.807408)
Version used: 2021-10-08T14:01:25Z

13.Summary:
Apache Tomcat is prone to a remote code execution vulnerability due to a bug
  in the way the JRE passes command line arguments to Windows.
13.Specific Result:
Installed version: 7.0.
Fixed version:     7.0.94
Installation
path / port:       443/tcp
13.Vulnerability Insight:
When running on Windows with enableCmdLineArguments enabled, the CGI Servlet
  is vulnerable to Remote Code Execution due to a bug in the way the JRE passes command line arguments to Windows.

22.NVT Name: SSL/TLS: Report Vulnerable Cipher Suites for HTTPS
22.Summary:
This routine reports all SSL/TLS cipher suites accepted by a service
  where attack vectors exists only on HTTPS services.
22.Specific Result:
'Vulnerable' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.1 protocol:
TLS_DHE_RSA_WITH_3DES_EDE_CBC_SHA (SWEET32)
TLS_RSA_WITH_3DES_EDE_CBC_SHA (SWEET32)
'Vulnerable' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.2 protocol:
TLS_DHE_RSA_WITH_3DES_EDE_CBC_SHA (SWEET32)
TLS_RSA_WITH_3DES_EDE_CBC_SHA (SWEET32)
22.Solution:
The configuration of this services should be changed so
  that it does not accept the listed cipher suites anymore.
  Please see the references for more resources supporting you with this task.
22.Affected Software/OS: Services accepting vulnerable SSL/TLS cipher suites via HTTPS.
22.Vulnerability Insight:
These rules are applied for the evaluation of the vulnerable cipher suites:
  - 64-bit block cipher 3DES vulnerable to the SWEET32 attack (CVE-2016-2183).
22.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Details:
SSL/TLS: Report Vulnerable Cipher Suites for HTTPS
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.108031)
Version used: 2021-09-20T09:01:50Z

25.Affected Software/OS: Apache Tomcat versions 8.5.0 to 8.5.40 and 9.0.0.M1 to 9.0.19.
25.Vulnerability Insight:
The fix for CVE-2019-0199 was incomplete and did not address HTTP/2 connection
  window exhaustion on write. By not sending WINDOW_UPDATE messages for the connection window (stream 0) clients
  are able to cause server-side threads to block eventually leading to thread exhaustion and a DoS.

31.Summary: PHP is improperly validating input from untrusted input.

Installation
path / port:       2021/tcp
31.Solution:
No solution was made available by the vendor. General solution options
  are to upgrade to a newer release, disable respective features, remove the product or replace the product
  by another one.
  Note: PHP versions 7.0.18 and 7.1.4 introduced a fix which was reverted again in version 7.0.19 / 7.1.5 respectively
  and the fix wasn't introduced again as of today (08-2020).
31.Affected Software/OS:

  Note: PHP versions 7.0.18 and 7.1.4 introduced a fix which was reverted again in version 7.0.19 / 7.1.5 respectively.
31.Vulnerability Insight:
main/streams/xp_socket.c in PHP misparses fsockopen calls, such as by
  interpreting fsockopen('127.0.0.1:80', 443) as if the address/port were 127.0.0.1:80:443, which is later
  truncated to 127.0.0.1:80. This behavior has a security risk if the explicitly provided port number
  (i.e., 443 in this example) is hardcoded into an application as a security policy, but the hostname
  argument (i.e., 127.0.0.1:80 in this example) is obtained from untrusted input.

34.Summary: Apache Tomcat is prone to a security bypass vulnerability.
34.Specific Result:
Installed version: 7.0.
Fixed version:     7.0.78
Installation
path / port:       443/tcp
34.Impact:
Successful exploitation will allow an attacker to
  exploit this issue to bypass certain security restrictions and perform
  unauthorized actions. This may lead to further attacks.
34.Solution:
Upgrade to version 9.0.0.M21, or 8.5.15,
  or 8.0.44, or 7.0.78 or later.
34.Affected Software/OS:
Apache Tomcat 9.0.0.M1 to 9.0.0.M20,
  Apache Tomcat 8.5.0 to 8.5.14,
  Apache Tomcat 8.0.0.RC1 to 8.0.43 and
  Apache Tomcat 7.0.0 to 7.0.77 on Windows
34.Vulnerability Insight:
The error page mechanism of the Java Servlet
  Specification requires that, when an error occurs and an error page is
  configured for the error that occurred, the original request and response are
  forwarded to the error page. This means that the request is presented to the
  error page with the original HTTP method. If the error page is a static file,
  expected behaviour is to serve content of the file as if processing a GET request,
  regardless of the actual HTTP method. Tomcat's Default Servlet did not do this.
  Depending on the original request this could lead to unexpected and undesirable
  results for static error pages including, if the DefaultServlet is configured to
  permit writes, the replacement or removal of the custom error page
34.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.

  Sharing a Processor can result in information leakage between requests including,

50.Summary: Apache Tomcat is prone to a security bypass vulnerability.
50.Specific Result:
Installed version: 7.0.
Fixed version:     7.0.78
Installation
path / port:       8443/tcp
50.Impact:
Successful exploitation will allow an attacker to
  exploit this issue to bypass certain security restrictions and perform
  unauthorized actions. This may lead to further attacks.
50.Solution:
Upgrade to version 9.0.0.M21, or 8.5.15,
  or 8.0.44, or 7.0.78 or later.
50.Affected Software/OS:
Apache Tomcat 9.0.0.M1 to 9.0.0.M20,
  Apache Tomcat 8.5.0 to 8.5.14,
  Apache Tomcat 8.0.0.RC1 to 8.0.43 and
  Apache Tomcat 7.0.0 to 7.0.77 on Windows
50.Vulnerability Insight:
The error page mechanism of the Java Servlet
  Specification requires that, when an error occurs and an error page is
  configured for the error that occurred, the original request and response are
  forwarded to the error page. This means that the request is presented to the
  error page with the original HTTP method. If the error page is a static file,
  expected behaviour is to serve content of the file as if processing a GET request,
  regardless of the actual HTTP method. Tomcat's Default Servlet did not do this.
  Depending on the original request this could lead to unexpected and undesirable
  results for static error pages including, if the DefaultServlet is configured to
  permit writes, the replacement or removal of the custom error page
50.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.

52.Summary:
Apache Tomcat is prone to a denial of service vulnerability in the HTTP/2
  implementation.
52.Specific Result:
Installed version: 8.5.31
Fixed version:     8.5.41
Installation
path / port:       8444/tcp
52.Vulnerability Insight:
The HTTP/2 implementation accepts streams with excessive numbers of SETTINGS
  frames and also permitts clients to keep streams open without reading/writing request/response data. By keeping
  streams open for requests that utilises the Servlet API's blocking I/O, clients are able to cause server-side
  threads to block eventually leading to thread exhaustion and a DoS.

60.Vulnerability Insight:

  send file code for the NIO HTTP connector in Apache Tomcat resulting in the

  Sharing a Processor can result in information leakage between requests including,
  not not limited to, session ID and the response body.

66.Summary: Apache Tomcat is prone to a remote code execution vulnerability.
66.Specific Result:
Installed version: 7.0.
Fixed version:     7.0.104
Installation
path / port:       443/tcp
66.Vulnerability Insight:
If:
  - an attacker is able to control the contents and name of a file on the server and
  - the server is configured to use the PersistenceManager with a FileStore and
  - the PersistenceManager is configured with sessionAttributeValueClassNameFilter='null' (the default unless a
    SecurityManager is used) or a sufficiently lax filter to allow the attacker provided object to be
    deserialized and
  - the attacker knows the relative file path from the storage location used by FileStore to the file the
    attacker has control over
  then, using a specifically crafted request, the attacker will be able to trigger remote code execution via
  deserialization of the file under their control. Note that all of conditions must be true for the attack to
  succeed.
66.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.

68.NVT Name: Apache Tomcat Privilege Escalation Vulnerability - Dec19 (Windows)
68.Summary: Apache Tomcat is prone to a privilege escalation vulnerability.
68.Specific Result:
Installed version: 8.5.31
Fixed version:     8.5.49
Installation
path / port:       8444/tcp
68.Solution:
Update to version 7.0.99, 8.5.49, 9.0.29 or later. As a mitigation disable
  Tomcat's JmxRemoteLifecycleListener and use the built-in remote JMX facilities provided by the JVM.
68.Vulnerability Insight:
When Tomcat is configured with the JMX Remote Lifecycle Listener, a local
  attacker without access to the Tomcat process or configuration files is able to manipulate the RMI registry to
  perform a man-in-the-middle attack to capture user names and passwords used to access the JMX interface. The
  attacker can then use these credentials to access the JMX interface and gain complete control over the Tomcat
  instance.
68.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.
Details:
Apache Tomcat Privilege Escalation Vulnerability - Dec19 (Windows)
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.143312)

78.Summary: Apache Tomcat is prone to a remote code execution vulnerability.
78.Specific Result:
Installed version: 7.0.
Fixed version:     7.0.104
Installation
path / port:       8443/tcp
78.Vulnerability Insight:
If:
  - an attacker is able to control the contents and name of a file on the server and
  - the server is configured to use the PersistenceManager with a FileStore and
  - the PersistenceManager is configured with sessionAttributeValueClassNameFilter='null' (the default unless a
    SecurityManager is used) or a sufficiently lax filter to allow the attacker provided object to be
    deserialized and
  - the attacker knows the relative file path from the storage location used by FileStore to the file the
    attacker has control over
  then, using a specifically crafted request, the attacker will be able to trigger remote code execution via
  deserialization of the file under their control. Note that all of conditions must be true for the attack to
  succeed.
78.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.

Apache Tomcat RCE Vulnerability - May20 (Windows)

82.NVT Name: Apache Tomcat Session Fixation Vulnerability (Nov 2012) - Windows
82.Summary: Apache Tomcat is prone to a session fixation vulnerability.
82.Specific Result:
Installed version: 7.0.
Fixed version:     6.0.37/7.0.33
Installation
path / port:       8080/tcp
82.Impact:
Successful exploitation will allow attackers to conduct session
  fixation attacks to hijack the target user's session.
82.Affected Software/OS:
Apache Tomcat version 6.0.21 through 6.0.36 and 7.x through
  7.0.32.
82.Vulnerability Insight:
java/org/apache/catalina/authenticator/FormAuthenticator.java
  in the form authentication feature does not properly handle the relationships between
  authentication requirements and sessions, which allows remote attackers to inject a request into
  a session by sending this request during completion of the login form, a variant of a session
  fixation attack.

Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.

116.NVT Name: Apache Tomcat HTTP Request Smuggling Vulnerability (Jul 2021) - Windows
116.Summary: Apache Tomcat is prone to an HTTP request smuggling vulnerability.
116.Specific Result:
Installed version: 8.5.31
Fixed version:     8.5.68
Installation
path / port:       8444/tcp
116.Affected Software/OS:
Apache Tomcat 8.5.x through 8.5.66, 9.0.0.M1 through 9.0.46
  and 10.0.0-M1 through 10.0.6.
116.Vulnerability Insight:
Apache Tomcat does not correctly parse the HTTP transfer-encoding
  request header in some circumstances leading to the possibility to request smuggling when used
  with a reverse proxy. Specifically: Tomcat incorrectly ignores the transfer-encoding header if
  the client declared it would only accept an HTTP/1.0 response. Tomcat honours the identify
  encoding and Tomcat does not ensure that, if present, the chunked encoding is the final encoding.

121.Summary:
The remote SSH server is configured to allow / support weak key
  exchange (KEX) algorithm(s).
121.Specific Result:
The remote SSH server supports the following weak KEX algorithm(s):
KEX algorithm                      | Reason
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1 | Using SHA-1
diffie-hellman-group1-sha1         | Using Oakley Group 2 (a 1024-bit MODP group) and SHA-1
121.Impact: An attacker can quickly break individual connections.
121.Solution:
Disable the reported weak KEX algorithm(s)
  - 1024-bit MODP group / prime KEX algorithms:
  Alternatively use elliptic-curve Diffie-Hellmann in general, e.g. Curve 25519.
121.Vulnerability Insight:
'- 1024-bit MODP group / prime KEX algorithms:
  Millions of HTTPS, SSH, and VPN servers all use the same prime numbers for Diffie-Hellman key
  exchange. Practitioners believed this was safe as long as new key exchange messages were generated
  for every connection. However, the first step in the number field sieve-the most efficient
  algorithm for breaking a Diffie-Hellman connection-is dependent only on this prime.
  A nation-state can break a 1024-bit prime.
121.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks the supported KEX algorithms of the remote SSH server.
  Currently weak KEX algorithms are defined as the following:
  - non-elliptic-curve Diffie-Hellmann (DH) KEX algorithms with 1024-bit MODP group / prime
  - ephemerally generated key exchange groups uses SHA-1
  - using RSA 1024-bit modulus key
Details:
Weak Key Exchange (KEX) Algorithm(s) Supported (SSH)

  - An error in the configured SecurityManager via a Tomcat utility method that
    is accessible to web applications.
  - An error in the configured SecurityManager via manipulation of the
    configuration parameters for the JSP Servlet.
  - An error in the ResourceLinkFactory implementation in Apache Tomcat that
    does not limit web application access to global JNDI resources to those
    resources explicitly linked to the web application.

145.NVT Name: Apache Tomcat Denial Of Service Vulnerability (Windows)
145.Summary: Apache Tomcat Server is prone to a denial of service (DoS) vulnerability.
145.Specific Result:
Installed version: 7.0.
Fixed version:     6.0.37/7.0.30
Installation
path / port:       8443/tcp
145.Impact:
Successful exploitation could allow remote attackers to cause a denial
  of service via a specially crafted request.
145.Solution: Apply patch or upgrade Apache Tomcat to 7.0.30 or 6.0.38 or later.
145.Affected Software/OS: Apache Tomcat version 6.x before 6.0.37 and 7.x before 7.0.30.
145.Vulnerability Insight:
Flaw due to improper validation of an error in the way CRLF sequences at the
  end of data chunks are processed by chunked transfer encoding.
145.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Details:
Apache Tomcat Denial Of Service Vulnerability (Windows)

150.NVT Name: Apache Tomcat Hash Collision Denial Of Service Vulnerability
150.Summary: Apache Tomcat Server is prone to a denial of service (DoS) vulnerability.
150.Specific Result:
Installed version: 7.0.
Fixed version:     5.5.35/6.0.35/7.0.23
Installation
path / port:       8443/tcp
150.Impact:
Successful exploitation could allow remote attackers to cause a denial
  of service via a specially crafted form sent in a HTTP POST request.
150.Solution: Apply patch or upgrade Apache Tomcat to 5.5.35, 6.0.35, 7.0.23 or later.
150.Affected Software/OS: Apache Tomcat version before 5.5.35, 6.x to 6.0.34 and 7.x to 7.0.22 on Windows.
150.Vulnerability Insight:
The flaw is due to an error within a hash generation function when
  computing hash values for form parameter and updating a hash table. This can
  be exploited to cause a hash collision resulting in high CPU consumption via
  a specially crafted form sent in a HTTP POST request.
150.Vulnerability Detection Method:

Apache Tomcat Hash Collision Denial Of Service Vulnerability

153.NVT Name: Apache Tomcat Multiple Security Bypass Vulnerabilities (Windows)
153.Summary: Apache Tomcat Server is prone to multiple security bypass vulnerabilities.
153.Specific Result:
Installed version: 7.0.
Fixed version:     5.5.34/6.0.33/7.0.12
Installation
path / port:       8443/tcp
153.Impact:
Successful exploitation could allows remote attackers to bypass intended
  access restrictions or gain sensitive information.
153.Solution: Upgrade Apache Tomcat to 5.5.34, 6.0.33, 7.0.12 or later.
153.Affected Software/OS: Apache Tomcat 5.5.x to 5.5.33, 6.x to 6.0.32 and 7.x to 7.0.11 on Windows.
153.Vulnerability Insight:
The flaws are due to errors in the HTTP Digest Access Authentication
  implementation,
  - which fails to check 'qop' and 'realm' values and allows to bypass
    access restrictions.
  - Catalina used as the hard-coded server secret in the
    DigestAuthenticator.java bypasses cryptographic protection mechanisms.
  - which fails to have the expected countermeasures against replay attacks.
153.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Details:
Apache Tomcat Multiple Security Bypass Vulnerabilities (Windows)
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.802415)

173.Summary:
This routine reports all Weak SSL/TLS cipher suites accepted
  by a service.
  NOTE: No severity for SMTP services with 'Opportunistic TLS' and weak cipher suites on port
  25/tcp is reported. If too strong cipher suites are configured for this service the alternative
  would be to fall back to an even more insecure cleartext communication.
173.Specific Result:
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.0 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.1 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.2 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
173.Solution:
The configuration of this services should be changed so
  that it does not accept the listed weak cipher suites anymore.
  Please see the references for more resources supporting you with this task.
173.Vulnerability Insight:
These rules are applied for the evaluation of the cryptographic
  strength:
  - RC4 is considered to be weak (CVE-2013-2566, CVE-2015-2808)
  - Ciphers using 64 bit or less are considered to be vulnerable to brute force methods
  and therefore considered as weak (CVE-2015-4000)
  - 1024 bit RSA authentication is considered to be insecure and therefore as weak
  - Any cipher considered to be secure for only the next 10 years is considered as medium
  - Any other cipher is considered as strong

176.Summary:
This routine reports all Weak SSL/TLS cipher suites accepted
  by a service.
  NOTE: No severity for SMTP services with 'Opportunistic TLS' and weak cipher suites on port
  25/tcp is reported. If too strong cipher suites are configured for this service the alternative
  would be to fall back to an even more insecure cleartext communication.
176.Specific Result:
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.1 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_SEED_CBC_SHA
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.2 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_SEED_CBC_SHA
176.Solution:
The configuration of this services should be changed so
  that it does not accept the listed weak cipher suites anymore.
  Please see the references for more resources supporting you with this task.
176.Vulnerability Insight:
These rules are applied for the evaluation of the cryptographic
  strength:
  - RC4 is considered to be weak (CVE-2013-2566, CVE-2015-2808)
  - Ciphers using 64 bit or less are considered to be vulnerable to brute force methods
  and therefore considered as weak (CVE-2015-4000)
  - 1024 bit RSA authentication is considered to be insecure and therefore as weak
  - Any cipher considered to be secure for only the next 10 years is considered as medium
  - Any other cipher is considered as strong
176.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Details:
SSL/TLS: Report Weak Cipher Suites
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.103440)

178.Summary:
The remote SSL/TLS service is prone to a denial of service (DoS)
  vulnerability.
178.Specific Result:
The following indicates that the remote SSL/TLS service is affected:
Protocol Version | Successful re-done SSL/TLS handshakes (Renegotiation) over an existing / already established SSL/TLS connection
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TLSv1.2          | 10
178.Impact:
The flaw might make it easier for remote attackers to cause a
  DoS (CPU consumption) by performing many renegotiations within a single connection.
178.Solution:
Users should contact their vendors for specific patch information.
  A general solution is to remove/disable renegotiation capabilities altogether from/in the affected
  SSL/TLS service.
178.Affected Software/OS:
Every SSL/TLS service which does not properly restrict
  client-initiated renegotiation.
178.Vulnerability Insight:
The flaw exists because the remote SSL/TLS service does not
  properly restrict client-initiated renegotiation within the SSL and TLS protocols.
  Note: The referenced CVEs are affecting OpenSSL and Mozilla Network Security Services (NSS) but
  both are in a DISPUTED state with the following rationale:
  > It can also be argued that it is the responsibility of server deployments, not a security
  library, to prevent or limit renegotiation when it is inappropriate within a specific environment.
  Both CVEs are still kept in this VT as a reference to the origin of this flaw.
178.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if the remote service allows to re-do the same SSL/TLS
  handshake (Renegotiation) over an existing / already established SSL/TLS connection.
Details:
SSL/TLS: Renegotiation DoS Vulnerability (CVE-2011-1473, CVE-2011-5094)
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.117761)
Version used: 2021-11-15T10:28:20Z

183.Summary:

  cleartext via HTTP.

http://172.28.130.190:8080/alfresco/api/-default-/public/cmis/versions/1.0/atom:"Alfresco -default- tenant"
http://172.28.130.190:8080/alfresco/api/-default-/public/cmis/versions/1.1/atom:"Alfresco -default- tenant"
http://172.28.130.190:8080/alfresco/api/-default-/public/cmis/versions/1.1/browser:"Alfresco -default- tenant"
http://172.28.130.190:8080/alfresco/s/?D=A:"Alfresco"
http://172.28.130.190:8080/alfresco/s/admin:"Alfresco"
http://172.28.130.190:8080/alfresco/s/index:"Alfresco"
http://172.28.130.190:8080/alfresco/webdav:"Alfresco DAV Server"
183.Impact:
An attacker could use this situation to compromise or eavesdrop on the
  HTTP communication between the client and the server using a man-in-the-middle attack to get access to
  sensitive data like usernames or passwords.
183.Solution:
Enforce the transmission of sensitive data via an encrypted SSL/TLS connection.
  Additionally make sure the host / application is redirecting all users to the secured SSL/TLS connection before
  allowing to input sensitive data into the mentioned functions.
183.Affected Software/OS:
Hosts / applications which doesn't enforce the transmission of sensitive data via an
  encrypted SSL/TLS connection.
183.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Evaluate previous collected information and check if the host / application is not
  enforcing the transmission of sensitive data via an encrypted SSL/TLS connection.

  The script is currently checking the following:

  - HTTP Basic Authentication (Basic Auth)

  - HTTP Forms (e.g. Login) with input field of type 'password'
Details:
Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information via HTTP

188.Summary: Apache Tomcat is prone to an information disclosure vulnerability in HTTP/2.
188.Specific Result:
Installed version: 8.5.31
Fixed version:     8.5.58
Installation
path / port:       8081/tcp
188.Vulnerability Insight:
If an HTTP/2 client exceeded the agreed maximum number of concurrent streams
  for a connection (in violation of the HTTP/2 protocol), it is possible that a subsequent request made on that
  connection could contain HTTP headers - including HTTP/2 pseudo headers - from a previous request rather than
  the intended headers. This could lead to users seeing responses for unexpected resources.
188.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.
Details:
Apache Tomcat HTTP/2 Vulnerability - Oct20 (Windows)
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.144736)
Version used: 2021-07-22T02:00:50Z

189.Summary:

The remote SSH server supports the following weak client-to-server encryption algorithm(s):

3des-cbc
aes128-cbc
aes192-cbc
aes256-cbc
arcfour
arcfour128
arcfour256
blowfish-cbc
cast128-cbc
rijndael-cbc@lysator.liu.se


The remote SSH server supports the following weak server-to-client encryption algorithm(s):

3des-cbc

aes192-cbc
aes256-cbc
arcfour
arcfour128
arcfour256
blowfish-cbc
cast128-cbc
rijndael-cbc@lysator.liu.se
189.Solution: Disable the reported weak encryption algorithm(s).
189.Vulnerability Insight:
'- The 'arcfour' cipher is the Arcfour stream cipher with 128-bit
  keys. The Arcfour cipher is believed to be compatible with the RC4 cipher [SCHNEIER]. Arcfour
  (and RC4) has problems with weak keys, and should not be used anymore.

  - The 'none' algorithm specifies that no encryption is to be done. Note that this method provides
  no confidentiality protection, and it is NOT RECOMMENDED to use it.

  - A vulnerability exists in SSH messages that employ CBC mode that may allow an attacker to
  recover plaintext from a block of ciphertext.
189.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks the supported encryption algorithms (client-to-server
  and server-to-client) of the remote SSH server.

  Currently weak encryption algorithms are defined as the following:

  - Arcfour (RC4) cipher based algorithms

  - none algorithm

  - CBC mode cipher based algorithms

191.NVT Name: SSL/TLS: Deprecated TLSv1.0 and TLSv1.1 Protocol Detection
191.Summary:
It was possible to detect the usage of the deprecated TLSv1.0
  and/or TLSv1.1 protocol on this system.
191.Specific Result: In addition to TLSv1.2+ the service is also providing the deprecated TLSv1.0 and TLSv1.1 protocols and supports one or more ciphers. Those supported ciphers can be found in the 'SSL/TLS: Report Supported Cipher Suites' (OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.802067) VT.
191.Impact:
An attacker might be able to use the known cryptographic flaws
  to eavesdrop the connection between clients and the service to get access to sensitive data
  transferred within the secured connection.

  Furthermore newly uncovered vulnerabilities in this protocols won't receive security updates
  anymore.
191.Solution:
It is recommended to disable the deprecated TLSv1.0 and/or
  TLSv1.1 protocols in favor of the TLSv1.2+ protocols. Please see the references for more
  information.
191.Affected Software/OS:
All services providing an encrypted communication using the
  TLSv1.0 and/or TLSv1.1 protocols.
191.Vulnerability Insight:
The TLSv1.0 and TLSv1.1 protocols contain known cryptographic
  flaws like:

  - CVE-2011-3389: Browser Exploit Against SSL/TLS (BEAST)

  - CVE-2015-0204: Factoring Attack on RSA-EXPORT Keys Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy
  Encryption (FREAK)
191.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Check the used TLS protocols of the services provided by this
  system.
Details:
SSL/TLS: Deprecated TLSv1.0 and TLSv1.1 Protocol Detection
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.117274)

aes192-cbc
aes256-cbc
arcfour
arcfour128
arcfour256
blowfish-cbc
cast128-cbc
rijndael-cbc@lysator.liu.se


The remote SSH server supports the following weak server-to-client encryption algorithm(s):

3des-cbc
aes128-cbc
aes192-cbc
aes256-cbc
arcfour
arcfour128
arcfour256
blowfish-cbc
cast128-cbc
rijndael-cbc@lysator.liu.se
196.Solution: Disable the reported weak encryption algorithm(s).
196.Vulnerability Insight:
'- The 'arcfour' cipher is the Arcfour stream cipher with 128-bit
  keys. The Arcfour cipher is believed to be compatible with the RC4 cipher [SCHNEIER]. Arcfour
  (and RC4) has problems with weak keys, and should not be used anymore.

  - The 'none' algorithm specifies that no encryption is to be done. Note that this method provides
  no confidentiality protection, and it is NOT RECOMMENDED to use it.

  - A vulnerability exists in SSH messages that employ CBC mode that may allow an attacker to
  recover plaintext from a block of ciphertext.
196.Vulnerability Detection Method:

  and server-to-client) of the remote SSH server.

  - none algorithm

  - CBC mode cipher based algorithms

207.Specific Result:
Installed version: 8.5.31
Fixed version:     8.5.58
Installation

207.Vulnerability Insight:

  the intended headers. This could lead to users seeing responses for unexpected resources.

211.NVT Name: SSL/TLS: Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange Insufficient DH Group Strength Vulnerability
211.Summary:
The SSL/TLS service uses Diffie-Hellman groups with insufficient strength
  (key size < 2048).
211.Impact: An attacker might be able to decrypt the SSL/TLS communication offline.
211.Solution:
Deploy (Ephemeral) Elliptic-Curve Diffie-Hellman (ECDHE) or use
  a 2048-bit or stronger Diffie-Hellman group (see the references).

  For Apache Web Servers:
  Beginning with version 2.4.7, mod_ssl will use DH parameters which include primes with lengths of more than 1024 bits.
211.Vulnerability Insight:
The Diffie-Hellman group are some big numbers that are used as base for
  the DH computations. They can be, and often are, fixed. The security of the final secret depends on the size
  of these parameters. It was found that 512 and 768 bits to be weak, 1024 bits to be breakable by really
  powerful attackers like governments.
211.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks the DHE temporary public key size.
Details:
SSL/TLS: Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange Insufficient DH Group Strength Vulnerab...
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.106223)
Version used: 2021-02-12T06:42:15Z

213.NVT Name: SSL/TLS: Certificate Signed Using A Weak Signature Algorithm
213.Summary:
The remote service is using a SSL/TLS certificate in the certificate chain that has been signed using a
  cryptographically weak hashing algorithm.
213.Specific Result:
The following certificates are part of the certificate chain but using insecure signature algorithms:

Subject:              CN=Alfresco Repository,OU=Unknown,O=Alfresco Software Ltd.,L=Maidenhead,ST=UK,C=GB
Signature Algorithm:  sha1WithRSAEncryption

Subject:              CN=Alfresco CA,O=Alfresco Software Ltd.,L=Maidenhead,ST=UK,C=GB
Signature Algorithm:  sha1WithRSAEncryption
213.Solution:
Servers that use SSL/TLS certificates signed with a weak SHA-1, MD5, MD4 or MD2 hashing algorithm will need to obtain new
  SHA-2 signed SSL/TLS certificates to avoid web browser SSL/TLS certificate warnings.
213.Vulnerability Insight:
The following hashing algorithms used for signing SSL/TLS certificates are considered cryptographically weak
  and not secure enough for ongoing use:

  - Secure Hash Algorithm 1 (SHA-1)

  - Message Digest 5 (MD5)

  - Message Digest 4 (MD4)

  - Message Digest 2 (MD2)

  Beginning as late as January 2017 and as early as June 2016, browser developers such as Microsoft and Google will begin warning users when visiting
  web sites that use SHA-1 signed Secure Socket Layer (SSL) certificates.

  NOTE: The script preference allows to set one or more custom SHA-1 fingerprints of CA certificates which are trusted by this routine. The fingerprints
  needs to be passed comma-separated and case-insensitive:

  Fingerprint1

  or

  fingerprint1, Fingerprint2
213.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Check which hashing algorithm was used to sign the remote SSL/TLS certificate.
Details:
SSL/TLS: Certificate Signed Using A Weak Signature Algorithm
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.105880)
Version used: 2021-10-15T11:13:32Z

215.Summary:
The remote host implements TCP timestamps and therefore allows to compute
  the uptime.
215.Specific Result:
It was detected that the host implements RFC1323/RFC7323.

The following timestamps were retrieved with a delay of 1 seconds in-between:
Packet 1: 927769553
Packet 2: 927770634
215.Impact:
A side effect of this feature is that the uptime of the remote
  host can sometimes be computed.
215.Solution:
To disable TCP timestamps on linux add the line 'net.ipv4.tcp_timestamps = 0' to
  /etc/sysctl.conf. Execute 'sysctl -p' to apply the settings at runtime.

  To disable TCP timestamps on Windows execute 'netsh int tcp set global timestamps=disabled'

  Starting with Windows Server 2008 and Vista, the timestamp can not be completely disabled.

  The default behavior of the TCP/IP stack on this Systems is to not use the
  Timestamp options when initiating TCP connections, but use them if the TCP peer
  that is initiating communication includes them in their synchronize (SYN) segment.

  See the references for more information.
215.Vulnerability Insight: The remote host implements TCP timestamps, as defined by RFC1323/RFC7323.
215.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Special IP packets are forged and sent with a little delay in between to the
  target IP. The responses are searched for a timestamps. If found, the timestamps are reported.
Details:
TCP timestamps
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.80091)

233.Summary: OpenSSL is prone to security-bypass vulnerability.

  sensitive information by conducting a man-in-the-middle attack. This may lead to other attacks.
233.Solution: Updates are available. Please see the references for more information.

OpenSSL does not properly restrict processing of ChangeCipherSpec
  messages, which allows man-in-the-middle attackers to trigger use of a zero-length master key in
  certain OpenSSL-to-OpenSSL communications, and consequently hijack sessions or obtain sensitive
  information, via a crafted TLS handshake, aka the 'CCS Injection' vulnerability.

244.Summary: jQuery is vulnerable to Cross-site Scripting (XSS) attacks.
244.Specific Result:
Installed version: 1.7.1
Fixed version:     1.9.0
Installation
path / port:       /js
244.Vulnerability Insight:
The jQuery(strInput) function does not differentiate selectors
  from HTML in a reliable fashion. In vulnerable versions, jQuery determined whether the input was
  HTML by looking for the '<' character anywhere in the string, giving attackers more flexibility
  when attempting to construct a malicious payload. In fixed versions, jQuery only deems the input
  to be HTML if it explicitly starts with the '<' character, limiting exploitability only to
  attackers who can control the beginning of a string, which is far less common.
244.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.
Details:
jQuery < 1.9.0 XSS Vulnerability
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.141636)

249.NVT Name: SSL/TLS: Deprecated SSLv2 and SSLv3 Protocol Detection
249.Summary:
It was possible to detect the usage of the deprecated SSLv2
  and/or SSLv3 protocol on this system.
249.Specific Result: In addition to TLSv1.0+ the service is also providing the deprecated SSLv2 and SSLv3 protocols and supports one or more ciphers. Those supported ciphers can be found in the 'SSL/TLS: Report Supported Cipher Suites' (OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.802067) VT.
249.Impact:
An attacker might be able to use the known cryptographic flaws to
  eavesdrop the connection between clients and the service to get access to sensitive data
  transferred within the secured connection.
  Furthermore newly uncovered vulnerabilities in this protocols won't receive security updates
  anymore.
249.Solution:
It is recommended to disable the deprecated SSLv2 and/or SSLv3
  protocols in favor of the TLSv1.2+ protocols. Please see the references for more information.
249.Affected Software/OS:
All services providing an encrypted communication using the
  SSLv2 and/or SSLv3 protocols.
249.Vulnerability Insight:
The SSLv2 and SSLv3 protocols contain known cryptographic
  flaws like:
  - CVE-2014-3566: Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption (POODLE)
  - CVE-2016-0800: Decrypting RSA with Obsolete and Weakened eNcryption (DROWN)
249.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Check the used SSL protocols of the services provided by this
  system.

264.Summary:
The remote SSL/TLS service is prone to a denial of service (DoS)
  vulnerability.
264.Specific Result:
The following indicates that the remote SSL/TLS service is affected:
Protocol Version | Successful re-done SSL/TLS handshakes (Renegotiation) over an existing / already established SSL/TLS connection
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TLSv1.0          | 10
TLSv1.1          | 10
TLSv1.2          | 10
264.Impact:
The flaw might make it easier for remote attackers to cause a
  DoS (CPU consumption) by performing many renegotiations within a single connection.
264.Solution:
Users should contact their vendors for specific patch information.
  A general solution is to remove/disable renegotiation capabilities altogether from/in the affected
  SSL/TLS service.
264.Affected Software/OS:
Every SSL/TLS service which does not properly restrict
  client-initiated renegotiation.
264.Vulnerability Insight:
The flaw exists because the remote SSL/TLS service does not
  properly restrict client-initiated renegotiation within the SSL and TLS protocols.
  Note: The referenced CVEs are affecting OpenSSL and Mozilla Network Security Services (NSS) but
  both are in a DISPUTED state with the following rationale:
  > It can also be argued that it is the responsibility of server deployments, not a security
  library, to prevent or limit renegotiation when it is inappropriate within a specific environment.
  Both CVEs are still kept in this VT as a reference to the origin of this flaw.
264.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if the remote service allows to re-do the same SSL/TLS
  handshake (Renegotiation) over an existing / already established SSL/TLS connection.
Details:
SSL/TLS: Renegotiation DoS Vulnerability (CVE-2011-1473, CVE-2011-5094)
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.117761)
Version used: 2021-11-15T10:28:20Z

270.Summary:
The remote SSL/TLS service is prone to a denial of service (DoS)
  vulnerability.
270.Specific Result:
The following indicates that the remote SSL/TLS service is affected:
Protocol Version | Successful re-done SSL/TLS handshakes (Renegotiation) over an existing / already established SSL/TLS connection
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TLSv1.0          | 10
TLSv1.1          | 10
TLSv1.2          | 10
270.Impact:
The flaw might make it easier for remote attackers to cause a
  DoS (CPU consumption) by performing many renegotiations within a single connection.
270.Solution:
Users should contact their vendors for specific patch information.
  A general solution is to remove/disable renegotiation capabilities altogether from/in the affected
  SSL/TLS service.
270.Affected Software/OS:
Every SSL/TLS service which does not properly restrict
  client-initiated renegotiation.
270.Vulnerability Insight:
The flaw exists because the remote SSL/TLS service does not
  properly restrict client-initiated renegotiation within the SSL and TLS protocols.
  Note: The referenced CVEs are affecting OpenSSL and Mozilla Network Security Services (NSS) but
  both are in a DISPUTED state with the following rationale:
  > It can also be argued that it is the responsibility of server deployments, not a security
  library, to prevent or limit renegotiation when it is inappropriate within a specific environment.
  Both CVEs are still kept in this VT as a reference to the origin of this flaw.
270.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if the remote service allows to re-do the same SSL/TLS
  handshake (Renegotiation) over an existing / already established SSL/TLS connection.
Details:
SSL/TLS: Renegotiation DoS Vulnerability (CVE-2011-1473, CVE-2011-5094)
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.117761)
Version used: 2021-11-15T10:28:20Z

272.Summary:
This routine reports all Weak SSL/TLS cipher suites accepted
  by a service.
  NOTE: No severity for SMTP services with 'Opportunistic TLS' and weak cipher suites on port
  25/tcp is reported. If too strong cipher suites are configured for this service the alternative
  would be to fall back to an even more insecure cleartext communication.
272.Specific Result:
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.0 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.1 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.2 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
272.Solution:
The configuration of this services should be changed so
  that it does not accept the listed weak cipher suites anymore.
  Please see the references for more resources supporting you with this task.
272.Vulnerability Insight:
These rules are applied for the evaluation of the cryptographic
  strength:
  - RC4 is considered to be weak (CVE-2013-2566, CVE-2015-2808)
  - Ciphers using 64 bit or less are considered to be vulnerable to brute force methods
  and therefore considered as weak (CVE-2015-4000)
  - 1024 bit RSA authentication is considered to be insecure and therefore as weak
  - Any cipher considered to be secure for only the next 10 years is considered as medium
  - Any other cipher is considered as strong
272.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Details:
SSL/TLS: Report Weak Cipher Suites
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.103440)
Version used: 2021-12-01T13:10:37Z

280.Summary: The application is missing the 'httpOnly' cookie attribute
280.Specific Result:
The cookies:
Set-Cookie: JSESSIONID=node0u93yk7qwhrte1dnh49pro7v74561.node0; Path=/
are missing the "httpOnly" attribute.
280.Solution: Set the 'httpOnly' attribute for any session cookie.
280.Affected Software/OS: Application with session handling in cookies.
280.Vulnerability Insight:
The flaw is due to a cookie is not using the 'httpOnly' attribute. This
  allows a cookie to be accessed by JavaScript which could lead to session hijacking attacks.
280.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Check all cookies sent by the application for a missing 'httpOnly' attribute

Missing `httpOnly` Cookie Attribute

281.Summary:
This routine reports all Weak SSL/TLS cipher suites accepted
  by a service.
  NOTE: No severity for SMTP services with 'Opportunistic TLS' and weak cipher suites on port
  25/tcp is reported. If too strong cipher suites are configured for this service the alternative
  would be to fall back to an even more insecure cleartext communication.
281.Specific Result:
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.0 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.1 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.2 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
281.Solution:
The configuration of this services should be changed so
  that it does not accept the listed weak cipher suites anymore.
  Please see the references for more resources supporting you with this task.
281.Vulnerability Insight:
These rules are applied for the evaluation of the cryptographic
  strength:
  - RC4 is considered to be weak (CVE-2013-2566, CVE-2015-2808)
  - Ciphers using 64 bit or less are considered to be vulnerable to brute force methods
  and therefore considered as weak (CVE-2015-4000)
  - 1024 bit RSA authentication is considered to be insecure and therefore as weak
  - Any cipher considered to be secure for only the next 10 years is considered as medium
  - Any other cipher is considered as strong
281.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Details:
SSL/TLS: Report Weak Cipher Suites
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.103440)
Version used: 2021-12-01T13:10:37Z

286.Summary:
The remote SSL/TLS service is prone to a denial of service (DoS)
  vulnerability.
286.Specific Result:
The following indicates that the remote SSL/TLS service is affected:
Protocol Version | Successful re-done SSL/TLS handshakes (Renegotiation) over an existing / already established SSL/TLS connection
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TLSv1.0          | 10
TLSv1.1          | 10
TLSv1.2          | 10
286.Impact:
The flaw might make it easier for remote attackers to cause a
  DoS (CPU consumption) by performing many renegotiations within a single connection.
286.Solution:
Users should contact their vendors for specific patch information.
  A general solution is to remove/disable renegotiation capabilities altogether from/in the affected
  SSL/TLS service.
286.Affected Software/OS:
Every SSL/TLS service which does not properly restrict
  client-initiated renegotiation.
286.Vulnerability Insight:
The flaw exists because the remote SSL/TLS service does not
  properly restrict client-initiated renegotiation within the SSL and TLS protocols.
  Note: The referenced CVEs are affecting OpenSSL and Mozilla Network Security Services (NSS) but
  both are in a DISPUTED state with the following rationale:
  > It can also be argued that it is the responsibility of server deployments, not a security
  library, to prevent or limit renegotiation when it is inappropriate within a specific environment.
  Both CVEs are still kept in this VT as a reference to the origin of this flaw.
286.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if the remote service allows to re-do the same SSL/TLS
  handshake (Renegotiation) over an existing / already established SSL/TLS connection.
Details:
SSL/TLS: Renegotiation DoS Vulnerability (CVE-2011-1473, CVE-2011-5094)
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.117761)
Version used: 2021-11-15T10:28:20Z

288.Summary:
This routine reports all Weak SSL/TLS cipher suites accepted
  by a service.
  NOTE: No severity for SMTP services with 'Opportunistic TLS' and weak cipher suites on port
  25/tcp is reported. If too strong cipher suites are configured for this service the alternative
  would be to fall back to an even more insecure cleartext communication.
288.Specific Result:
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.0 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.1 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.2 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
288.Solution:
The configuration of this services should be changed so
  that it does not accept the listed weak cipher suites anymore.
  Please see the references for more resources supporting you with this task.
288.Vulnerability Insight:
These rules are applied for the evaluation of the cryptographic
  strength:
  - RC4 is considered to be weak (CVE-2013-2566, CVE-2015-2808)
  - Ciphers using 64 bit or less are considered to be vulnerable to brute force methods
  and therefore considered as weak (CVE-2015-4000)
  - 1024 bit RSA authentication is considered to be insecure and therefore as weak
  - Any cipher considered to be secure for only the next 10 years is considered as medium
  - Any other cipher is considered as strong
288.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Details:
SSL/TLS: Report Weak Cipher Suites
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.103440)

299.NVT Name: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information via HTTP
299.Summary:
The host / application transmits sensitive information (username, passwords) in
  cleartext via HTTP.
299.Specific Result:
The following URLs requires Basic Authentication (URL:realm name):
http://172.28.131.24:9200/:"security" charset="UTF-8"
299.Impact:
An attacker could use this situation to compromise or eavesdrop on the
  HTTP communication between the client and the server using a man-in-the-middle attack to get access to
  sensitive data like usernames or passwords.
299.Solution:
Enforce the transmission of sensitive data via an encrypted SSL/TLS connection.
  Additionally make sure the host / application is redirecting all users to the secured SSL/TLS connection before
  allowing to input sensitive data into the mentioned functions.
299.Affected Software/OS:
Hosts / applications which doesn't enforce the transmission of sensitive data via an
  encrypted SSL/TLS connection.
299.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Evaluate previous collected information and check if the host / application is not
  enforcing the transmission of sensitive data via an encrypted SSL/TLS connection.
  The script is currently checking the following:
  - HTTP Basic Authentication (Basic Auth)
  - HTTP Forms (e.g. Login) with input field of type 'password'
Details:
Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information via HTTP
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.108440)

302.NVT Name: SSL/TLS: Deprecated TLSv1.0 and TLSv1.1 Protocol Detection
302.Summary:
It was possible to detect the usage of the deprecated TLSv1.0
  and/or TLSv1.1 protocol on this system.
302.Specific Result: In addition to TLSv1.2+ the service is also providing the deprecated TLSv1.0 and TLSv1.1 protocols and supports one or more ciphers. Those supported ciphers can be found in the 'SSL/TLS: Report Supported Cipher Suites' (OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.802067) VT.
302.Impact:
An attacker might be able to use the known cryptographic flaws
  to eavesdrop the connection between clients and the service to get access to sensitive data
  transferred within the secured connection.
  Furthermore newly uncovered vulnerabilities in this protocols won't receive security updates
  anymore.
302.Solution:
It is recommended to disable the deprecated TLSv1.0 and/or
  TLSv1.1 protocols in favor of the TLSv1.2+ protocols. Please see the references for more
  information.
302.Affected Software/OS:
All services providing an encrypted communication using the
  TLSv1.0 and/or TLSv1.1 protocols.
302.Vulnerability Insight:
The TLSv1.0 and TLSv1.1 protocols contain known cryptographic
  flaws like:
  - CVE-2011-3389: Browser Exploit Against SSL/TLS (BEAST)
  - CVE-2015-0204: Factoring Attack on RSA-EXPORT Keys Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy
  Encryption (FREAK)
302.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Check the used TLS protocols of the services provided by this
  system.
Details:
SSL/TLS: Deprecated TLSv1.0 and TLSv1.1 Protocol Detection

330.NVT Name: SSL/TLS: Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange Insufficient DH Group Strength Vulnerability
330.Summary:
The SSL/TLS service uses Diffie-Hellman groups with insufficient strength
  (key size < 2048).
330.Impact: An attacker might be able to decrypt the SSL/TLS communication offline.
330.Solution:
Deploy (Ephemeral) Elliptic-Curve Diffie-Hellman (ECDHE) or use
  a 2048-bit or stronger Diffie-Hellman group (see the references).

  For Apache Web Servers:
  Beginning with version 2.4.7, mod_ssl will use DH parameters which include primes with lengths of more than 1024 bits.
330.Vulnerability Insight:
The Diffie-Hellman group are some big numbers that are used as base for
  the DH computations. They can be, and often are, fixed. The security of the final secret depends on the size
  of these parameters. It was found that 512 and 768 bits to be weak, 1024 bits to be breakable by really
  powerful attackers like governments.
330.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks the DHE temporary public key size.
Details:

(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.106223)

334.NVT Name: SSL/TLS: Certificate Signed Using A Weak Signature Algorithm
334.Summary:
The remote service is using a SSL/TLS certificate in the certificate chain that has been signed using a
  cryptographically weak hashing algorithm.
334.Specific Result:
The following certificates are part of the certificate chain but using insecure signature algorithms:

Subject:              1.2.840.113549.1.9.1=#737570706F72742E61786564612E636F6D,CN=Deployment Configuration,OU=R&D,O=Axeda Corporation,L=Foxboro,ST=Massachusetts,C=US
Signature Algorithm:  sha1WithRSAEncryption
334.Solution:
Servers that use SSL/TLS certificates signed with a weak SHA-1, MD5, MD4 or MD2 hashing algorithm will need to obtain new
  SHA-2 signed SSL/TLS certificates to avoid web browser SSL/TLS certificate warnings.
334.Vulnerability Insight:
The following hashing algorithms used for signing SSL/TLS certificates are considered cryptographically weak
  and not secure enough for ongoing use:

  - Secure Hash Algorithm 1 (SHA-1)

  - Message Digest 5 (MD5)

  - Message Digest 4 (MD4)

  - Message Digest 2 (MD2)

  Beginning as late as January 2017 and as early as June 2016, browser developers such as Microsoft and Google will begin warning users when visiting
  web sites that use SHA-1 signed Secure Socket Layer (SSL) certificates.

  NOTE: The script preference allows to set one or more custom SHA-1 fingerprints of CA certificates which are trusted by this routine. The fingerprints
  needs to be passed comma-separated and case-insensitive:

  Fingerprint1

  or

  fingerprint1, Fingerprint2
334.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Check which hashing algorithm was used to sign the remote SSL/TLS certificate.

SSL/TLS: Certificate Signed Using A Weak Signature Algorithm
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.105880)

353.NVT Name: OpenSSH Denial of Service And User Enumeration Vulnerabilities (Windows)
353.Summary: openssh is prone to denial of service and user enumeration vulnerabilities.
353.Specific Result:
Installed version: 7.2
Fixed version:     7.3
Installation
path / port:       22/tcp
353.Impact:
Successfully exploiting this issue allows
  remote attackers to cause a denial of service (crypt CPU consumption) and
  to enumerate users by leveraging the timing difference between responses
  when a large password is provided.
353.Solution: Upgrade to OpenSSH version 7.3 or later.
353.Vulnerability Insight:
Multiple flaws exist due to:
  - The auth_password function in 'auth-passwd.c' script does not limit password
    lengths for password authentication.
  - The sshd in OpenSSH, when SHA256 or SHA512 are used for user password hashing
    uses BLOWFISH hashing on a static password when the username does not exist
    and it takes much longer to calculate SHA256/SHA512 hash than BLOWFISH hash.
353.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.
Details:
OpenSSH Denial of Service And User Enumeration Vulnerabilities (Windows)
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.809121)
Version used: 2021-10-15T11:13:32Z
353.Product Detection Result:
Product: cpe:/a:openbsd:openssh:7.2
Method: OpenSSH Detection Consolidation
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.108577)

354.Summary: openssh is prone to multiple vulnerabilities.
354.Specific Result:
Installed version: 7.2
Fixed version:     7.4
Installation
path / port:       22/tcp
354.Impact:
Successfully exploiting this issue allows
  local users to obtain sensitive private-key information, to gain privileges,
  conduct a senial-of-service condition and allows remote attackers to execute
  arbitrary local PKCS#11 modules.
354.Solution: Upgrade to OpenSSH version 7.4 or later.
354.Vulnerability Insight:
Multiple flaws exist due to:
  - An 'authfile.c' script does not properly consider the effects of realloc
    on buffer contents.
  - The shared memory manager (associated with pre-authentication compression)
    does not ensure that a bounds check is enforced by all compilers.
  - The sshd in OpenSSH creates forwarded Unix-domain sockets as root, when
    privilege separation is not used.
  - An untrusted search path vulnerability in ssh-agent.c in ssh-agent.
  - NULL pointer dereference error due to an out-of-sequence NEWKEYS message.
354.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.
Details:
OpenSSH Multiple Vulnerabilities Jan17 (Windows)
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.810325)
Version used: 2021-10-12T09:28:32Z
354.Product Detection Result:
Product: cpe:/a:openbsd:openssh:7.2
Method: OpenSSH Detection Consolidation
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.108577)

360.Summary:
The remote SSL/TLS service is prone to a denial of service (DoS)
  vulnerability.
360.Specific Result:
The following indicates that the remote SSL/TLS service is affected:
Protocol Version | Successful re-done SSL/TLS handshakes (Renegotiation) over an existing / already established SSL/TLS connection
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TLSv1.0          | 10
TLSv1.1          | 10
TLSv1.2          | 10
360.Impact:
The flaw might make it easier for remote attackers to cause a
  DoS (CPU consumption) by performing many renegotiations within a single connection.
360.Solution:
Users should contact their vendors for specific patch information.
  A general solution is to remove/disable renegotiation capabilities altogether from/in the affected
  SSL/TLS service.
360.Affected Software/OS:
Every SSL/TLS service which does not properly restrict
  client-initiated renegotiation.
360.Vulnerability Insight:
The flaw exists because the remote SSL/TLS service does not
  properly restrict client-initiated renegotiation within the SSL and TLS protocols.
  Note: The referenced CVEs are affecting OpenSSL and Mozilla Network Security Services (NSS) but
  both are in a DISPUTED state with the following rationale:
  > It can also be argued that it is the responsibility of server deployments, not a security
  library, to prevent or limit renegotiation when it is inappropriate within a specific environment.
  Both CVEs are still kept in this VT as a reference to the origin of this flaw.
360.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks if the remote service allows to re-do the same SSL/TLS
  handshake (Renegotiation) over an existing / already established SSL/TLS connection.
Details:
SSL/TLS: Renegotiation DoS Vulnerability (CVE-2011-1473, CVE-2011-5094)
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.117761)
Version used: 2021-11-15T10:28:20Z

364.Summary:
This routine reports all Weak SSL/TLS cipher suites accepted
  by a service.
  NOTE: No severity for SMTP services with 'Opportunistic TLS' and weak cipher suites on port
  25/tcp is reported. If too strong cipher suites are configured for this service the alternative
  would be to fall back to an even more insecure cleartext communication.
364.Specific Result:
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.0 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.1 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
'Weak' cipher suites accepted by this service via the TLSv1.2 protocol:
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_MD5
TLS_RSA_WITH_RC4_128_SHA
364.Solution:
The configuration of this services should be changed so
  that it does not accept the listed weak cipher suites anymore.
  Please see the references for more resources supporting you with this task.
364.Vulnerability Insight:
These rules are applied for the evaluation of the cryptographic
  strength:
  - RC4 is considered to be weak (CVE-2013-2566, CVE-2015-2808)
  - Ciphers using 64 bit or less are considered to be vulnerable to brute force methods
  and therefore considered as weak (CVE-2015-4000)
  - 1024 bit RSA authentication is considered to be insecure and therefore as weak
  - Any cipher considered to be secure for only the next 10 years is considered as medium
  - Any other cipher is considered as strong
364.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Details:
SSL/TLS: Report Weak Cipher Suites
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.103440)
Version used: 2021-12-01T13:10:37Z

366.NVT Name: SSL/TLS: Deprecated TLSv1.0 and TLSv1.1 Protocol Detection
366.Summary:
It was possible to detect the usage of the deprecated TLSv1.0
  and/or TLSv1.1 protocol on this system.
366.Specific Result: In addition to TLSv1.2+ the service is also providing the deprecated TLSv1.0 and TLSv1.1 protocols and supports one or more ciphers. Those supported ciphers can be found in the 'SSL/TLS: Report Supported Cipher Suites' (OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.802067) VT.
366.Impact:
An attacker might be able to use the known cryptographic flaws
  to eavesdrop the connection between clients and the service to get access to sensitive data
  transferred within the secured connection.
  Furthermore newly uncovered vulnerabilities in this protocols won't receive security updates
  anymore.
366.Solution:
It is recommended to disable the deprecated TLSv1.0 and/or
  TLSv1.1 protocols in favor of the TLSv1.2+ protocols. Please see the references for more
  information.
366.Affected Software/OS:
All services providing an encrypted communication using the
  TLSv1.0 and/or TLSv1.1 protocols.
366.Vulnerability Insight:
The TLSv1.0 and TLSv1.1 protocols contain known cryptographic
  flaws like:
  - CVE-2011-3389: Browser Exploit Against SSL/TLS (BEAST)
  - CVE-2015-0204: Factoring Attack on RSA-EXPORT Keys Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy
  Encryption (FREAK)
366.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Check the used TLS protocols of the services provided by this
  system.
Details:
SSL/TLS: Deprecated TLSv1.0 and TLSv1.1 Protocol Detection
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.117274)
Version used: 2021-07-19T08:11:48Z

373.NVT Name: SSL/TLS: Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange Insufficient DH Group Strength Vulnerability
373.Summary:
The SSL/TLS service uses Diffie-Hellman groups with insufficient strength
  (key size < 2048).
373.Impact: An attacker might be able to decrypt the SSL/TLS communication offline.
373.Solution:
Deploy (Ephemeral) Elliptic-Curve Diffie-Hellman (ECDHE) or use
  a 2048-bit or stronger Diffie-Hellman group (see the references).

  For Apache Web Servers:
  Beginning with version 2.4.7, mod_ssl will use DH parameters which include primes with lengths of more than 1024 bits.
373.Vulnerability Insight:
The Diffie-Hellman group are some big numbers that are used as base for
  the DH computations. They can be, and often are, fixed. The security of the final secret depends on the size
  of these parameters. It was found that 512 and 768 bits to be weak, 1024 bits to be breakable by really
  powerful attackers like governments.
373.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Checks the DHE temporary public key size.

(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.106223)

375.Summary:
The remote host implements TCP timestamps and therefore allows to compute
  the uptime.
375.Specific Result:
It was detected that the host implements RFC1323/RFC7323.

The following timestamps were retrieved with a delay of 1 seconds in-between:
Packet 1: 691152625
Packet 2: 691152899
375.Impact:
A side effect of this feature is that the uptime of the remote
  host can sometimes be computed.
375.Solution:
To disable TCP timestamps on linux add the line 'net.ipv4.tcp_timestamps = 0' to
  /etc/sysctl.conf. Execute 'sysctl -p' to apply the settings at runtime.

  To disable TCP timestamps on Windows execute 'netsh int tcp set global timestamps=disabled'

  Starting with Windows Server 2008 and Vista, the timestamp can not be completely disabled.

  The default behavior of the TCP/IP stack on this Systems is to not use the
  Timestamp options when initiating TCP connections, but use them if the TCP peer
  that is initiating communication includes them in their synchronize (SYN) segment.

  See the references for more information.
375.Vulnerability Insight: The remote host implements TCP timestamps, as defined by RFC1323/RFC7323.
375.Vulnerability Detection Method:
Special IP packets are forged and sent with a little delay in between to the
  target IP. The responses are searched for a timestamps. If found, the timestamps are reported.
Details:
TCP timestamps
(OID: 1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.80091)
Version used: 2020-08-24T08:40:10Z
